issue.title: Legal/licensing requirements for bundling
issue.body:
I'm currently in the process of rewriting my Toolkit project to version 3.0. This version will be dropping jQuery and will be entirely written in ES6. I'm at a crossroad where a good portion of functionality can be solved by lodash, and was wondering what legal/licensing requirements there are if I bundle parts of lodash in the "production" ready Toolkit code, found here: https://github.com/titon/toolkit/tree/3.0/dist

I'm assuming that I would simply have to place the license in the file. If there's anything else let me know. Or if you guys are against this approach as well. Full credit will be given throughout.

comment.body: Sounds great, thanks for the quick reply!

comment.body:
Awesome@milesj!

Lodash is available under [an MIT license](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/master/LICENSE). It looks like you're MIT too so I can see just adding a mention to the copyright headers there (similar to how we've added Underscore to ours). If you want you can always run it by when you're done and I can give feedback.

issue.title: _.delete/_.remove for objects using a path.
issue.body:
It would be great to be able to remove a value from an object, including it's key using a path just like `_.get` and `_.set`.

```javascript
_.remove(object, 'a[0].b.c');
```

comment.body: The next step is for someone to create a PR for `_.unset`.

issue.title: Support hint param for sortedIndex
issue.body: [As it is now](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/master/lodash.js#L2767), the first index checked is naturally the midpoint of the array. This is a good default but sometimes the programmer knows some information about a likely insertion position for the value. Would be great if lodash supported an additional `hint` param!

comment.body: Absolutely, it's fine the way it is! Sorry if it sounded like I was complaining. I just think it could be improved. My particular use case is inserting many values that are close together. According to my benchmarks, using `sortedIndex` is slower than `push`ing then `sort`ing. If I could use the previous index as an initial parameter, it would make things much faster!
